  <title>GWeather.LocationLevel</title>
  <p>The size/scope of a particular <link xref="GWeather.Location"/>.</p>  <p>Locations form a hierarchy, with a <link xref="GWeather.LocationLevel"/>.world
location at the top, divided into regions or countries, and so on.
Countries may or may not be divided into "adm1"s, and "adm1"s may
or may not be divided into "adm2"s. A city will have at least one,
and possibly several, weather stations inside it. Weather stations
will never appear outside of cities.</p>  <p>Building a database with <link xref="GWeather.location_get_world"/> will never
create detached instances, but deserializing might.</p>

<terms>
<item>
<title><code>LocationLevel.WORLD</code></title>
  <p>A location representing the entire world.</p>
</item>
<item>
<title><code>LocationLevel.REGION</code></title>
  <p>A location representing a continent or
other top-level region.</p>
</item>
<item>
<title><code>LocationLevel.COUNTRY</code></title>
  <p>A location representing a "country" (or
other geographic unit that has an ISO-3166 country code)</p>
</item>
<item>
<title><code>LocationLevel.ADM1</code></title>
  <p>A location representing a "first-level
administrative division"; ie, a state, province, or similar
division.</p>
</item>
<item>
<title><code>LocationLevel.ADM2</code></title>
  <p>A location representing a subdivision of a
<link xref="GWeather.LocationLevel"/>.adm1 location, or a direct subdivision of
a country that is not represented in a <link xref="GWeather.LocationEntry"/>.</p>
</item>
<item>
<title><code>LocationLevel.CITY</code></title>
  <p>A location representing a city</p>
</item>
<item>
<title><code>LocationLevel.WEATHER_STATION</code></title>
  <p>A location representing a
weather station.</p>
</item>
<item>
<title><code>LocationLevel.DETACHED</code></title>
  <p>A location that is detached from the
database, for example because it was loaded from external storage
and could not be fully recovered. The parent of this location is
the nearest weather station.</p>
</item>
</terms>
